@TAP7a "Yeah any AI making these kinds of choices in a real world application should be required to give some sort of explanatory output."
As I said, the AI shouldn't be making these choices -- it should be an input that a human uses to make the choice. At the moment, it generally will be, since humans are used to making their own decisions about grading assignments, so they also find it natural to make their own decisions about whether something is plagiarized.

But "explainable AI" is a huge research area at the moment. You're absolutely right that systems need to be able to explain why they came to their decisions. Black-box systems don't stand up to scrutiny, and it's now well-understood that arguments such as "The computer made the decision, so it can't be discriminatory" don't hold water. This means that both developers and users of AI systems have quite a strong incentive to avoid systems that can't justify the outcome.

@SurrealDynamics "How do you prove that you are the author if a machine says otherwise just by reading?"
First, as I posted in my previous comment just now, you shouldn't be accused of plagiarism just on the say-so of some detection tool. There should always be a human judgement applied, and plagiarism cases should be brought based on specifics, not just on a general similariy score.

But to address your question, you prove that you're the author by showing the history of the document in the form of your drafts, in which the text evolves. So make sure you save your drafts -- they're useful as backups in case of data loss, too.

